<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-325-364  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 325 364.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  April 2 1990 v9 n7 p60(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Postmaster promises cost cuts. (Postmaster General Anthony M.andO;Frank on the US Postal Service's automation investment) (NewsRoundup) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smith, James M.; Power, Kevin; Grimm, Vanessa Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Postal ServiceMail ProcessingAutomationPlanningBudgetingNational GovernmentOptical Character ReadersCost ReductionUnited States. Postal Service.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Postmaster Promises Cost CutsandM;Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank promised recently the Postal Service'sautomation investment eventually will drive operating costs below inflation.andM;&quot;For the first quarter of 1990, we've operated at 1 percent below inflation,&quot;he said, adding he wants to bring costs down another 1 percent.andM;The service is meeting the cost reduction goals set by its board ofgovernors, said John G. Mulligan, senior assistant postmaster general for theOperations Support Group.andP;  But he said the multiline optical characterreaders (MLOCRs) that replaced the single-line OCRs are so new, the servicecan get only a snapshot of the savings captured.andM;The service's plan calls for more automation to be phased in over three yearsto meet the 1995 automation target.andP;  Now between 30 percent and 40 percent ofall mail is handled automatically using bar code and MLOCR technologies.andM;Starting in 1992, the service plans to use wide area bar code readers thatcan scan an entire envelope.andP;  The readers now scan only a small portion ofeach envelope.andO;</TEXT></DOC>